DIV2.P:
“COUNT Piper, first Minister to the King, his Privy Counsellor, and great Marshal; Count Reinschild Field Marshal and Privy Counsellor; the Majors General, Slippenback, Stackleberg, Rosen and Hamilton; the Colonels, Prince Wir∣temberg, Prince Applegreen, Count Horn, and Prince Rhenschild, 6 Lieutenant Colonels, 4 Majors, 2 Captains of Horse, 20 of Foot, 1 Lieutenant of Horse, 2 of the King's Life∣Guards, 1 of the King's Quarter-Masters of Re∣giments, 53 Lieutenants of Foot, 3 Adjutants, 1 Trumpeter, 4 Surgeons, 3 Clerks of Regi∣ments, 21 under Officers of Foot and Horse, 2528 Horse and Foot Soldiers, 12 Hautboys, 4 Surgeons Mates, 24 Drums: Of the Chancery were Prisoners, the Secretary Cederkielm, the Se∣cretary Dickbon, 2 Writers in the Chancery; the King's Chaplain, and Mr. Morbergh; Prisoners;
in all 2978, taken from the Swedes, the following Trophies, 34 Standards of Horse, 29 of Dragoons, 69 Colours, of which 6 are of the Regiments of Guards; in all 134 Standards and Colours. In this Battle only 4 Cannon were ta∣ken, because the Swedes brought no more into the Action, 1 pair of Kettle Drums of Silver, belonging to the Guards, 3 Pair of Copper. In the intrim, Prince Menzickoff, who march'd the 28th in pursuit of the Swedes, could not overtake them till the 30th, notwithstanding all the Expedition he made; for they retir'd precipitately, leaving behind them the greatest part of their Baggage, that Day his Highness discover'd them posted very Advantageously near the small Town of Perecolocza, at the Foot of the Mountain on the Bank of the Bo∣risthenes, and was inform'd by the Quarter-Masters of a Regiment, and some Machians, who were taken Prisoners; that the King of Sweden had pass'd the Boristhenes, by swim∣ming with Major General Spar and Lagereroon, and 300 of the best mounted Troopers about 3 Hous before, and had left on this Side the re∣mains of his Army, under the command of Ge∣neral Lewenhaupt: Some said the King was wounded the Day before the Battle in the Head, others in the Ankle; and indeed, so various were the Stories concerning him, that we cannot here repeat them; he retired as they say to Ockzakow, a Town at the Mouth of the Bay, in the Country of the Budzaick Tar∣tars; but we heard afterwards that he was gone to ender, on the River Niester, and that he was Royally us'd by the Turks; where we must leave him, and return to Prince Menzic∣koff;
who without loss of time, caus'd his Body of Men, which did not exceed 9000 to advance against the Swedes, and some Prisoners having ad∣ded, that they believed they might be dispos'd to surrender themselves on terms of Capitulation: His Highness summon'd them to yield, intimating to them, that they were depriv'd of all Means of escaping by a Retreat, and that if they rejected his offer, they were not to hope for Quarter, but be all put to the Sword.”

LETTER.P:
“YESTERDAY in the Evening came in 5 Posts from England, whereupon being inform'd that your Excellency will not be here till the end of the Week, I would not fail to give you an Account without delay, according to my Promise; and for due Execution of my Orders of what has happen'd last in England, concern∣ing your Affairs; I therefore acquaint your Ex∣cellency, that on the 14th and 15th of the last Month, the Persons engag'd in Arresting your Excellency appeared before the Lord Chief Ju∣stice in the Court, which we call the Queen's∣Bench; her Majesty's two Secretaries of State, the Lord Sunderland and Mr. Boyle being pre∣sent there, with a great Number of other Per∣sons of Note, who were no less desirous of seeing the Criminals brought to condign Pu∣nishment, then they were concern'd at the In∣sult offer'd to your Excellency. The Indict∣ment was laid against Thomas Morten, and other Creditors of your Excellency; as also against one Benson, an Attorney em∣ployed in taking out the executory Orders for Arresting your Excellency, and the two Bailiffs who actually Arrested you; the Par∣ties being heard, after a long and considera∣ble Plea, made by the Queen's Attorney Gene∣neral, Sollicitor General, and other Persons learn'd in the Law, acting for her Majesty, the Jury consisting of Gentlemen of Distinction, and plentiful Estates in the Country; more especially Chosen on that Occasion, declared the Persons mention'd in the Indictment, ex∣cept
one oung, against whom no Evidence ap∣pear'd, to be convicted of having Comploted and Conspired together to Arrest your Excellencies Person, notwithstanding they knew the same to be invested with the Character of an Ambassador; as also having by that Means occasion'd a Mis-understanding betwixt the Queen and his Czarish Majesty, and of having assaulted, ar∣rested, imprisoned, and abus'd the said Person of your Excellency; the Jury having thus given in your Verdict, and the Case being so Extraordi∣nary, of very great importance, altogether New, and without President in our Courts of England, the Lord Chief Justice could not take upon him to determine it, but referr'd the Point relating to the Privileges of Ambassadors, that is to say, how far the Laws of the Realm may reach for the Punishing of those who violate them to a Scrutiny, which is to be made the next Term before him, assisted hy the other Judges of the Kingdom: This is the present State of the Business, it is not absolutely decided, but the indicted Persons are found guilty of the Fact, and Punishment will be solemnly debated before all the Judges of the King∣dom, the Case having never before been known in our Law, therefore if you please tis Requisite that your Excellency have a little more Patience to see the final deter∣mination of this Process, and content your self in waiting with your wonted Prudence, and Mo∣deration for the issue of the Queen's efforts in prosecuting the Criminals, since her Majesty has omitted nothing on her Part for that purpose, for if our Formalities of Injustice appear'd long and tedious; 'tis what cannot in any wise be reme∣died;
it being part of our Constitution, to which every individual Person in the Kingdom is ob∣lig'd to submit; I have already had the honour to Treat with your Excellency so often upon this Subject, that I hope you are sensible there∣of, and of the Queen's most sincere Intentions to do every thing that lies in her Majesty's power for repairing the injury done to your Person, and Character, I doubt not but the whole will terminate in the common Satisfaction, I am with profound respect,”
